[2] Cholera - Angola (Huambo)
Date: Tue 16 Jan 2007
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Angola Press [edited]
<http://www.angolapress-angop.ao/noticia-e.asp?ID=502110>

Public health services of Huambo city have detected 10 new cholera cases in
the past 24 hours in various wards on the outskirts of the region, with no
fatalities, thereby raising the number of cases to 503, 35 of whom have
died, ANGOP has learned.
The cholera outbreak in Huambo city, in the central plateau region with the
same name, was officially declared on 24 Nov 2006, with the disease
affecting the outskirts of the area: Macolocolo, Kaquereuwa, Rua do
Comericio, Benfica, Belem do Huambo, Kanhe, Kapango, and the suburban areas
of Cruzeiro, Cacilhas and Santo Antonio.
Currently, 24 patients are hospitalized in the special cholera treatment
center in the regional hospital of Huambo, and the local health authorities
continue to consider the consumption of non-treated water and the poor
condition of drainage infrastructure to be the main causes of the spread of
the disease.
In the Angolan capital (Luanda), the cholera outbreak was officially
declared on 19 Feb 2006, with the 1st case having been identified on 13 Feb
2006, and later, it spread countrywide, initially through the coastal
regions of the country, and is currently affecting 17 provinces, with the
exception of northeast Lunda Sul province.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[A map of Angola, where Huambo and Lunda Sul can be found, may be seen at
<http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/angola.pdf>. - Mod.LL]
