[3] Cholera - Tanzania (Arusha)
Date: Tue 16 Jan 2007
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Arusha Times [edited]
<http://www.reliefweb.int/rw/RWB.NSF/db900SID/STED-6XHTDG?OpenDocument>

The New Year started in Arusha with fresh outbreaks of cholera, and by 8
Jan 2007, 8 victims had been admitted at Levolosi health center, which had
also been designated a cholera camp. The Municipal Medical Officer, Dr
Solomon Ole Logilunore told the Arusha Times that the epidemic was still a
threat in Arusha. Four cases were reported on 1 Jan 2007, 5 on 2 Jan, 6
patients on 5 Jan, 6 on 7 Jan and 4 on 8 Jan 2007, all coming from within
the municipality and the Arumeru areas bordering the municipality.
He mentioned the affected areas as being Mbauda, Unga Limited, Sokon One,
and Sombetini in the municipality, while the Arumeru areas are Olasiti,
Matevesi, FFU; Sanawari ya Juu, Ilboru and Ngaramtoni.
Dr Logilunore further explained that cholera claimed 3 lives out of the 300
cases that were attended to at Levolosi, Mount Meru hospital and Mkonoo
camps since the epidemic was 1st reported on 26 Oct 2006.
He said 191 out of the 300 cases came from the municipality, so the
municipal council should be working hard to control the epidemic by
improving hygiene in social and commercial centers. Centers targeted in the
hygiene improvement drive include schools, markets, bus stands, mosques,
churches and food and drinks service centers as well as the town pay toilets.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[A map of Tanzania showing the city and province of Arusha in the
northeast, close to Mt Kilimanjaro, can be found at
<http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/tanzania.pdf>. Brent
Barrett also contributed a similar report. - Mod.LL]
