[4] Cholera - Zambia
Date: Mon 15 Jan 2007
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Int Fed of Red Cross And Red Crescent Societies (IFRC) [edited]
<http://www.reliefweb.int/rw/RWB.NSF/db900SID/EVOD-6XGK25?OpenDocument>

Every year, the onset of the rainy season triggers cholera outbreaks in
Zambia. On 15 Oct 2006, a cholera case was officially recorded at the
Lukanga fishing swamps in Mposhi District (Central Province). Though the
cases later increased, the situation was contained within the month without
any fatalities. Another case was reported on 30 Oct 2006 in Chiengi
District, Luapula Province, and by the end of November 2006, a cumulative
total of 115 cases and 5 deaths had been recorded.
Prior to the October 2006 outbreaks, another outbreak had occurred in
Lusaka, the capital city, after cases that had begun to be reported in
August 2005 had increased. As of 31 Jan 2006, 2415 cases (with 21 deaths)
had been recorded. By 5 Apr 2006, the total case number stood at 7615, of
which 5991 were recorded in Lusaka District alone.
The densely populated areas in the capital have very poor sanitation
conditions, making them prone to cholera outbreaks. By 7 Mar 2006, the
outbreak had affected 6 other provinces as follows: Central Province (443
cases), Copper Belt Province (233), Eastern Province (221), Luapula
Province (31), North-Western Province (2), and Southern Province (314).
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[A map of Zambia can be found at
<http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/zambia.pdf>.
- Mod.LL]
